#SRCA
#D Langton's Self-Replication Loop 
#D Langton's self-replicating structure is a loop constructed in
#D two-dimensional, 8-state, 5-neighbor cellular space, based on
#D one of Codd's elements, known as a periodic emitter. The 86-cell
#D loop is basically a closed data path, consisting of a string of
#D core cells in state 1, surrounded by sheath cells in state 2.
#D  
#D Data paths are capable of transmitting data in the form of 
#D signals, which are packets of two co-traveling states: the signal
#D state itself (state 4, 5, 6, or 7) followed by the state 0. 
#D
#D The signals contained within the loop cycle through it, comprising 
#D the instructions for replication, i.e., the ``genome.'' 
#D
#D As each such signal encounters the arm junction it is duplicated, 
#D with one copy propagating back around the loop again and the other 
#D copy propagating down the arm, where it is translated as an 
#D instruction when it reaches the end of the arm. 
#D
#D In executing the instructions the arm extends itself and folds, 
#D ultimately resulting in a daughter loop, also containing the 
#D genome needed to replicate.
#D 
#D Author: C. Langton
